---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const title = "GCP VPC egress costs: how to estimate outbound transfer";
const description =
  "A practical method to estimate GCP outbound transfer: split by destination (internet, cross-region, inter-zone, CDN origin), convert metrics to GB/month, and validate boundaries.";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What usually drives VPC egress costs?",
    a: "Internet egress is the main driver for many apps, but cross-region and inter-zone patterns can create large hidden costs in distributed systems.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do I estimate quickly?",
    a: "Estimate monthly outbound GB by destination using a blended effective rate, then refine by splitting the top traffic flows.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do I validate?",
    a: "Validate real outbound GB from flow logs or metrics, validate cross-zone/region traffic, and validate CDN origin egress separately from edge bandwidth.",
  },
];
---
<GuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/guides/gcp-vpc-egress-costs"
  lastUpdated="2026-01-22"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p>
    Transfer costs are easiest to control when you split traffic into billable categories and validate boundaries. This guide
    is a practical workflow you can apply before you deploy or when you see an unexpected bill.
  </p>

  <h2>1) Split traffic into destinations</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Internet egress (end users, SaaS, third-party APIs)</li>
    <li>Cross-region (replication, DR, multi-region services)</li>
    <li>Cross-zone / inter-zone (distributed services)</li>
    <li>Origin egress to CDN (cache fill)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>2) Convert usage to GB/month</h2>
  <p>
    Use a representative time window and convert to monthly GB. If you only have RPS, multiply by average response size to
    approximate transfer volume.
  </p>
  <p>
    Tools: <a href="/calculators/api-response-size-transfer-calculator/">Response transfer</a>,{" "}
    <a href="/calculators/rps-to-monthly-requests-calculator/">RPS â†’ requests</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>3) Apply effective blended rates for planning</h2>
  <p>
    For early budgeting, a blended effective rate per GB is fine. The real value is the breakdown: it tells you what to
    cache, compress, or route differently.
  </p>
  <p>
    Tool: <a href="/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator/">Egress cost calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Validation checklist</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Validate cross-zone and cross-region traffic from distributed systems (common hidden drivers).</li>
    <li>Validate compression and payload sizes for high-volume endpoints.</li>
    <li>Validate CDN origin egress separately from edge bandwidth and cache hit rate.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator/">Egress</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/api-response-size-transfer-calculator/">Transfer</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-bandwidth-cost-calculator/">CDN bandwidth</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/network-transfer-costs/">Network transfer costs</a>
  </div>
</GuideLayout>

